Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This dataset contains information of approximatley 10,000 movie titles collected from the movie database (TMDb). The information provided is the popularity of the movie, budget invested for the movie, revenue and profit from the movie, title, cast members, director, homepage, tagline, keywords, overview, runtime, genres, production_companies, release_date, vote_count, vote_average and release_year.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

Research Question 1 (Profit Change in regard to years)

Research Question 2 (Movies with the highest and lowest profit)

Research Question 3 (Are average votes getting better by the years?)

Research Question 4 ( What are the most frequent elements in each categorical section )

Research Question 5 ( Do Higher budget movies produce higher profit ? )

Research Question 6 ( Does Popularity influence profit and is it influenced by the runtime? )

Research Question 2 (Movies with the highest and lowest profit)¶

In [68]:
#Exploring titles with most and lowest profit(loss)

maxmin_df=df.copy()
High=maxmin_df[maxmin_df['profit'].notnull()].sort_values(by=['profit'],ascending=True).tail(10)
Low=maxmin_df[maxmin_df['profit'].notnull()].sort_values(by=['profit'],ascending=False).tail(10)
High=High.plot(x='original_title',y='profit',rot=60,figsize=(25,8),marker='o',color='green',title='10 Highest Profit Movies ')
Low=Low.plot(x='original_title',y='profit',rot=60,figsize=(25,8),marker='o',color='blue',title='10 Lowest Profit Movies ')
High.set_xlabel('Movies')
High.set_ylabel('Profit')
Low.set_xlabel('Movies')
Low.set_ylabel('Profit')
Out[68]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Profit')

Multiple representation of top 10 and bottom 10 could have been implemented but a simple line with a marker at each movie signifies for the noticable difference between adjacent movies.¶

Conclusions¶

Research Question 1 (Profit Change in regard to years) : From our given data set we have observed a rise in profit in the movie industry from 1960 onwards.

Research Question 2 (Movies with the highest and lowest profit) : Avatar was the movie with most profit while The Warrior's Way suffered the greatest loss.

Research Question 3 (Are average votes getting better by the years?) : The average votes are decreasing year after year And a significant growth in the number of titles and voters is noted since more people have interest in watching movies hence more people are capable of voting across the years. However due to the weak correlation between number of votes and average votes of 0.25 it is difficult to say that movie ratings are getting better or worse but it is safe to say their is a rise of number of movies and number of voters.

Research Question 4 ( What are the most frequent elements in each categorical section ) : CAST = Robert De Niro , PRODUCTION_COMPANIES = Universal Pictures , GENRES = Drama , DIRECTOR = Woddy Allen

Research Question 5 ( Do Higher budget movies produce higher profit ? ) : In our dataset it was not always the case since between 2.0 and 2.5 in budgetary terms their was a massive profit. While loss was identified with budget greater than 4.0, there was a correlation of 0.53 that seemed to affirm that the relationship wasn't strong and dependant on other variables altogether.

Research Question 6 ( Does Popularity influence profit and is it influenced by the runtime? ) : Movies of length between 100 and 200 mins exhibit much more popularity than others as well as popular movies tended to be more profitable and they do have a positive correlation of (0.6) which is reasonable and abids with common sense. The more Popular the movie the more the audience is attracted to the commotion and hence greater revenue resulting in a higher profit.

Limitations¶

1 - Due to time constraints working on the project, I wanted to explore pandas, seaborne, matplotlib and python's capablities much more. This would've optimized my coding conduct and efficient use of functions. For instance I wanted to split genres, cast, production companies and directors into multiple rows. A movie with 3 genres and 2 cast members would require the same row to be repeated 6 TIMES so that the genres and cast do not coincide with each other at the same column section, or I would have come up with a whole different technique!

This would have provided me with decoupled rows that would have increased the size of the data set but would allow much more interesting insights to be extracted such as correlation between genres and popularity, cast member and profitabili-ty etc.

2 - Budget and revenue of certain movies could not be recalled and has impacted heavily its consequent rows being participants in major numerical anayltics.

3 - Time and location of movie screening or screening span could have provided more insights for deciding optimal timing to screen a title.
